Docker:

Docker is a containerization tool that packages an application along with all its dependencies into a container, so it runs the same in every environment.
We use Docker to avoid environment issues, make application setup easier, and deploy applications faster.
                          OR.
Docker is a containerization platform that uses OS-level virtualization to run applications in isolated containers.
It helps ensure environment consistency, improves deployment speed, optimizes resource usage compared to virtual machines, and is commonly used in CI/CD pipelines and microservices architectures.

Note: 
Unlike virtual machines, Docker containers are lightweight, start faster, and share the host OS, making them more efficient.
The main purpose of Docker is to ensure that the application runs the same across different environments like development, testing, and production. This helps avoid common issues such as â€œit works on my machine.

Image vs Container:

In docker there are docker container and docker image 

In Docker, an image is a blueprint and a container is a running instance of that image.
A Docker image contains the application code, libraries, dependencies, and configuration. It is read-only and used to create containers.
A Docker container is created from an image and represents the running application. Containers are lightweight, isolated, and can be started, stopped, or deleted easily.
Multiple containers can be created from the same image.

Image: Template / blueprint
Container: Running application

